Barack Obama is the fourth President of the United States to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
US President Barack Obama comes to Oslo, Norway for 26 hours to receive the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth US President in history.
In addition, he receives the diploma as well as the medal and a cheque of $1.4 million for his extraordinary efforts to intensify world diplomacy and cooperation among the peoples.
The White House chief arrives tomorrow with his wife Michelle in the Northwestern metropolis and will be busy all the time.
First, he visits the Nobel Institute, where he meets for the first time with the five committee members who elected him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple then scheduled a meeting with the Norwegian King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit reaches its peak with the ceremony at which Obama takes over the Prestige Prize.
He is the fourth President of the United States, but only the third to receive the prize directly in office.
The White House has already announced that Obama will talk about the war in Afghanistan when the prize is taken over.
The president does not want to evade this issue because he knows he is taking the prize as a president who is currently at war in two countries.
He intensified the war effort a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forget to highlight.
At the ceremony, Obama also received the gold medal, diploma and cheque for ten million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
The money he intends to donate to charity, but he has not yet decided on a concrete charitable work.
The event programme will then include a banquet with the President and his wife, attended by the King and Queen of Norway, the Prime Minister and 250 invited guests.
Obama was very reticent about the price from the beginning.
For example, he said he feels he doesn’t deserve the prize.
He also repeated several times that the price is not just for him, but for all those who strive for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he stated that for him this is "call to action".
