USA: Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom
It is almost weird with what student ambition Barack Obama, the president with his reputation of the smartest, repeats his predecessor’s strategy on the Afghanistan issue, which he himself considered the stupidest.
When he finally sweated out his eagerly-anticipated Afghanistan doctrine, it turned out that he wrote it off using the copy paper from the Bush Iraq scenario three years ago.
Not only does he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text himself, he even uses the name of the Bush Declaration of January 2007 as the name of his own declaration: "New way forward" without hesitation.
Even three years ago, he criticized the Bush idea of sending fresh contingents to Iraq, which was plagued by the civil war, as an "irresponsible and, in its consequence, catastrophic decision."
However, the following months showed that the Bush strategy, based on military recommendations, was the only possible and very successful one, so that today the news about Iraq is no longer being talked about at all.
This did not improve Bush’s reputation, as he objectively left his successor with a much more appreciative initial situation than expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will repeat itself.
The military once again asked him to increase the contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of Afghanistan Operation General Stanley McCristal, who, despite the habits of subordination, harshly criticized the timid gunmen in the White House.
He called for 40,000 soldiers to reverse the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but came up with no better idea and so he cheated the general by 10,000 soldiers.
From Europe, he has squeezed the promise for another 5,000, even if he himself originally expected at least 10,000.
Most problematic about the entire Obama strategy is his plan to withdraw troops from Afghanistan in 18 months, and to complete this process within three years. The entire Obama doctrine leaves more questions than answers.
Some doubt that the halved increase will have the same effect as the measure in Iraq.
Despite the brotherly war of recent years, the Iraqi society is relatively well-structured, and its leaders honor the values.
The Afghan situation is characterized by the contraindication - no one can be trusted and no agreements are kept.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, who are accustomed to changing their minds every day.
The political institutions, even if they were formally established correctly, remain only fictitious structures behind which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to grow.
The balancing of interests between the different ethnic groups is unusually complicated, especially because of the unclearness of the circumstances, which further complicates the influences of Pakistan and Iran.
The establishment of a "capable state", which is the minimalistic goal of the whole operation, is also very unrealistic.
Time horizon of Obama’s strategy stunned by his voluntarism
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only deteriorated further and now it is on the verge of explosion.
Believe that the little soldiers who have broken out in the war cry about the "early return" can create a miracle here, only a truly romantic soul who is not impressed by facts.
From a political point of view, the date for the withdrawal of troops is pure irresponsibility, because the Taliban will accept this as the indirect confession of the American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that Europeans’ willingness to participate in the fighting in Afghanistan is diminishing.
Europe’s politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their voters in what way the security of Germany or Italy is related to the war in the Hindu Kush mountain foreland.
Another possible factor that can radically influence the situation is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions do not affect Iranians, the United States will face a very serious question as to whether the problem can not be solved with troops.
This question must be answered in the period in which America moves after Obama to withdraw victoriously from Afghanistan.
Any solution will also mean a dramatic change in the Afghan situation.
The only consolation for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years to go until the presidential election, and so there is still enough time for him to resort to a different strategy if it turns out to be a total failure.
