Czech discovery: a substance that also works in 'stealed' HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the compound does not act as strongly on common virus variants as one of the already existing drugs.
The disease AIDS cannot be cured.
However, patients can prolong their life and prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the body.
However, their intake is accompanied by a number of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of the virus propagation also leads to the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which no medicines are more effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, from the VSCHT (Chemical-Technological University) Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with virus resistance.
They have demonstrated that the substances called metalocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the propagation of the HIV virus.
The metalocarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block virus propagation in a different way than all drugs used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists come up with new ‘improved’ compounds, which have been prepared on the basis of the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus protein.
The metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two diverse cages composed of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Insidious and resistant virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV-virus cleavage caused by the HIV protease, no mature infectious virus particles would arise.
If we turn off the HIV protease, we also turn off the propagation of the virus in the patient's body, the scientists explain in the press report published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the paper, published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically further modified.
A little weaker but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was tested in the test tube, also against their resistant variants obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of the metalocarboranes on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as with the clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect on the resistant variants against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action, as well as its other properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical designs, makes the metalocarboranes interesting compounds for further research aimed at the development of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlina Rezacova, Head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology of the Institutes of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics.
