Can Islam be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters have voted for a ban on building minarets and concerns about the alleged Islamization of Europe are widespread, John Bowen, an American academic, has written a sound and well-considered report on whether Muslims can be integrated — and integrated — into one of Europe’s declared most secularized societies.
Some readers will read this new book out of admiration for the author's last work: "Why the French Don't Like Headscarves" (2006), an elegant and densely argued study of a dispute that the country shared and occupied over a decade and whose effects can still be felt today.
Bowen’s latest book offers a broader and bolder spectrum.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what politicians and the media are saying about Islam in France, but what is really happening in the field.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes that now offer the 5 to 6 million Muslims in France, as Bowen calls "Islamic freedoms."
He’s a good listener, he retells debates between teachers and students about the issues that worries them the most.
Should a Muslim marry in a mosque or a town hall (or both)?
Should young Muslims be taught about the evolution and rights of homosexuals?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim to use an interest-oriented banking system to get a mortgage?
It is these seemingly profane affairs, he claims, that make up everyday life, quite in contrast to the political dramas that the media employ.
The author recognizes a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, none of them with a known name, possibly with the exception of Tarik Ramadan, a Swiss-born Arab-Muslim scholar and academic.
This new generation is trying to open up the debate about how it is possible to be a good Muslim on the one hand and a good citizen on the other hand in a modern secular society.
They don’t have all the arguments on their side.
The conservatives are suspicious of the idea of a French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists who interviewed Bowen mostly disagree with their Salafist counterparts – supporters of purist Sunni Islam associated with Saudi Arabia – who today show a small but influential presence among Europe’s Muslims.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
