Last year, 60-year-olds and older people accounted for nearly 22 percent of Shanghai’s reported residents, while the birth rate was below one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, head of the Shanghai City Population and Family Planning Commission, said that couples in procreative age must have babies to "help reduce the ratio of aging population and alleviate the labour shortage of the future."
Shanghai will soon be "as old -- but not as rich -- as developed countries, like Japan and Sweden," she said.
A gradual relaxation
Enshrined in the country’s 1978 constitution, China’s one-child policy is arguably the most controversial decree introduced by the ruling Communist Party to this day.
Couples who violate this policy face enormous fines -- up to three times their annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination in their workplaces.
Chinese officials have attributed to this policy that the critical use of natural land resources could be avoided, whereas human rights representatives have condemned abuses in enforcing the policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who have already had a child to aborte.
Many couples also had sex-selective abortions performed, creating an unnaturally high ratio of men to women.
In recent years, government officials for the population have gradually weakened their stance on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities, and cases where both husband and wife were single children -- and in 2007 the tone of many harsh slogans was mitigated.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Population Research at the University of Beijing, said that government officials have recently even discussed more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children with a single partner.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births in July.
Posters that taught families to have only one child were replaced almost overnight by guidelines detailing who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for approval.
The city administration has sent municipal employees and volunteers for family planning to visit couples at home and push information sheets under the doors.
She also asked to provide psychological and financial advice for those who have more than one child.
The response was not exactly encouraging, family planning representatives said.
Disappointing reaction
Although officials from a rural small town in the outskirts of Shanghai said that there was a boom in applications from couples who want a second child after the campaign started, the urban districts, on the other hand, report no change.
In the municipality of Huinan with a population of 115,000, as an example, only four to five applications are still received per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say the expected number of births in the city for 2010 will still be around 165,000 despite the campaign -- slightly higher than 2009, but lower than 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee of the Shanghai municipality of Caolu, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want to have more children.
They want to give their first one the best, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would like to have two children and that this is legally permitted.
But they, like many Chinese, only have a small amount of government health and life insurance.
Without a social network, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West mistakenly view the one-child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a civil engineer whose wife is pregnant with her first child in her seventh month.
Yes, we are being robbed of the possibility of having more than one child.
The problem is not just politics.
The problem is money.
Other couples give psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the HR manager, said she only wants a child because she was also a single child. "We were the center of the family and used to have everyone take care of us.
We’re not used to taking care of others and we don’t really want to.”
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old who owns a translation company, said it bluntly.
For middle-class parents with a double career, which lowers the birth rate, he said, it’s all about being successful and you have to be selfish for it.
The age group of today’s 20- to 39-year-olds grew up watching their parents struggle during the early days of the Chinese capitalism experiment and they don’t want such a life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child, he said, poses huge demands on the time of the parents.
A mother must give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there's the space question -- "You have to rebuild your apartment" -- and life planning -- "When the child is 9 months old, you must already have a resume ready for the best preschools."
Most of his friends are willing to go through this once, Chen said, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to reach a higher standard of living, he said.
We do not want to make too many sacrifices.
UN Group Drafts Plan to Reduce Emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- which has so far been characterized by wild poses and mutual accusations -- has re-established a focus on Friday with the publication of a document that records an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with the industrialized nations having to bear the greatest burdens in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a definitive political agreement on the regulation of greenhouse gases, has highlighted both the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But it was seen as important progress in a negotiation that runs out of time as next week more than 100 top politicians from all over the world will arrive in Copenhagen.
The text, formulated by a specially created UN working group, is silent about the amount of money that rich countries should give to poor countries so that they can cope with global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for key issues, including how industrialized and emerging economies can limit their carbon emissions and how high the upper limit of global temperature rise should be that policy makers would support.
The process is given a great deal of flexibility, according to John Coequyt, senior representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what UN climate change leader Yvo de Boer called “the big picture.”
It shows the outline of a possible agreement in which the developed nations would jointly reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 limits, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent in the same period.
Together, the countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community has also boosted Friday’s talks by promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the effects of climate change – from mastering floods and droughts to preventing deforestation.
Friday nevertheless brought the same verbal fireworks that had determined the talks last week.
U.S. Special Envoy for Climate Change Todd Stern has rejected formulations calling for mandatory greenhouse gas emission reductions for developed countries, compared to voluntary reductions for major emerging economies, if these are not funded by the industrialized nations.
This move announced that the Obama administration is running a tougher line with China than the Bush administration did not even two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without major emerging countries rising up and taking action, Stern, who also complained that the text does not go far enough to ensure that the cuts could be confirmed by outsiders as well.
Stern made his statement an hour after China’s Deputy Foreign Secretary He Yafei’s statement, stating that the leading American climate negotiator either lacked “reason” or was “highly irresponsible” by him, saying earlier this week that the United States would not help China financially to cope with global warming.
Due to the future economic direction of the major world powers at stake, breaking lines have opened up both within the industrialized nations and between the industrialized nations and the emerging markets.
The current struggle relates equally to the saving of individual economies, as well as the saving of the planet, with China and the United States fighting for their corresponding commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific necessity to take bolder action.
Ricardo Ulate, a Costa Rican delegate, said it is not surprising that the big powers are fighting to determine who should bear the cost of curbing greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have moved to act more aggressively to hold the countries with very high greenhouse gas levies accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game that will lead to a new economic hegemony, according to Ulate, who also serves as a regional climate change advisor for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the effects of climate change stated that they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although leading participants say the talks will lead at best to a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island Countries, with 43 members, presented a 24-page draft treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said that the small island states' offensive "exerts political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now united and demand action from emerging markets, such as China and India.
The talks got a new urgency as the delegates focused on the fact that most open issues still need to be clarified before the arrival of the leaders in order to reach an agreement.
High-ranking representatives, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister, got off their planes and rushed through the Bella Center corridors to meetings behind closed doors and press conferences to mark claims being negotiated during next week.
The sheer scale of the gathering -- 13,000 people going in and out of the convention center every day, guitar-playing activists hosting nighttime shows mocking the countries they think are betraying and selling, and drafting contracts hand-to-hand rather than email -- is already a challenge.
The intensity is only just building up: Almost all the important ministers are here now and from Wednesday 60 government leaders will be in Copenhagen.
We’re coming to the upper league,” said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president of global politics at Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
