He hopes that the new service will eventually connect Britain to an international rail network of fast, reliable trains and connect the major metropolitan areas of the Midlands, the North and Scotland to London.
The neglected province could become vibrant commuter cities, working hours would be radically reduced, and switching from plane and car to rail would reduce national carbon emissions and traffic jams on the roads.
In theory, the three major parties believe in this vision.
But the many billions of pounds needed to build a new national rail network, the inevitable planning battle, and fears of environmental damage could still brake the British high-speed rail.
