Lord Adonis will announce whether he believes this plan should be continued or not, but the lengthy public consultation and planning measures mean that a final decision will not be made until after the parliamentary elections.
But even if it sets the wheels in motion, the rail network must be built in sections.
The trains would first have to switch from the high-speed lines to existing rail lines in the north of Birmingham, which would keep the journey time between London and Scotland at more than three hours.
This is considered to be a decisive knock-off point in order to ensure a change from the aircraft to the railway, a guideline for the rail revolution.
