Manager Revolution or the End of Strategic Early Enlightenment?
If nothing changes in the leadership of the great French companies, our struggle for the development of economic intelligence has been in vain ...
For over a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies in relation to its employees, said the position of the companies vis-à-vis the consumers before the marketing revolution: It is determined for the staff to join "values" to impose the best, as it used to be on the consumer products designed by the technicians in the factory.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution has given the strategies of conquering the markets in the place ... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products separately factors the preferences of the customers again regularly!
A demobilization of employees can lead to fatal demoralization.
The suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of a much larger phenomenon that affects employees in particular.
This demobilization has a negative impact on the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially those of R&D and, more importantly, those of economic intelligence.
In fact, the IE (Intelligence Economique <0x3D> Economic Intelligence) calls for "a proactive approach and a forward-looking view from all parties involved"; it claims from the employees a commitment that completely contradicts the instructions of authoritarian management.
That is why we call for an operational revolution, which would be to place employees at the center of the company’s concerns on an equal footing with customers.
The very conditional benefit of internal opinion polls
Will the internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its wage earners, stimulate this revolution in terms of management practice?
I'm afraid not.
- First, because I was able to find that, in the face of a new situation, after many detours, the whole structure finally gets to do first and foremost what it has always done.
Also because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – increases proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
And finally, because most leaders have a greatly simplified idea of human behavior.
Their interpretation of psychology has emerged from the major engineering schools.
They adopt, through intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory recently reactivated by the American “neurosciences” and unknowingly widely disseminated by research institutes and the media.
Thus, and by suggesting that it is possible to use the "lever" (sic) for employee engagement, a recent survey by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr strengthens the leadership in an attitude towards a mechanistic control system unsuitable for today’s world.
Identify and measure the mobilization factors
Instead, an operational revolution necessary for the smooth functioning of modern enterprises presupposes the adoption of a definitive view of human behavior.
It consists in integrating a fundamental protocol into any consideration or practice of governance: for wage earners, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to realize part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Currently, only the studies from the multifunctional analysis adopt this concept of employee motivation.
These studies have shown that they assess their company on the basis of a predetermined Doxa, which allows them to assess what it offers to achieve their life goals through their perceived image of the company.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, corporate executives can control, predict and anticipate their “social performance” and put their human resource management back in the right place.
In this way, they create a fertile soil that is favorable for the coordinated development of robust and efficient economic intelligence.
Oslo Speech: The “Justice War” Brings Obama Praise from the Right
On Friday, the American Right welcomed Barack Obama’s speech in Oslo and was pleased that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize had defended the notion of “just war” against the enemies of the United States.
The Conservatives, who mocked Obama’s award on October 9, applauded this time the president’s speech, following the example of former vice presidential candidate Sarah Palin in the 2008 election.
I liked what he said, Palin explained, the face of the right wing of the Republican Party in USA Today, adding that she herself had raised the topic of a “sometimes necessary” war in her memoirs recently published.
The war is, of course, the last thing I think the Americans want to do, but it is necessary.
We need to stop the terrorists down there, she says.
Obama, who inherited two wars from his predecessor George W. Bush, the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan, on Thursday in Oslo endeavoured to justify the use of force; a way to explain his decision nine days ago to send 30,000 additional soldiers to Afghanistan.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, expressed the opinion that the president had done “very good work” in Oslo.
I found that the speech was really very good, the former president of the House of Representatives rejoiced, especially recognizing the reference to "the existence of evil in the world" in the words of Obama.
In some parts, I felt this speech was entirely historical, Ginrich explained, who was interviewed in the radio show "The Takeaway".
The former MP, who is considered by some to be a possible candidate for the Republican nomination for the 2012 presidential election, said he was pleased to have seen a “left-wing president” reminding members of the Nobel Committee that they “are not free and could not hand out a price for peace if the use of force did not exist.”
For Michael Gerson, former writer of George W. Bush and now editor of the Washington Post, Obama made “a very American speech.”
In addition to portraying himself as a "cosmopolitan" as "he always does," he has "spoken like an American president" when he pointed out that Europeans "live like a security bubble they didn't create themselves and don't do much to protect it," Gerson said.
