Turkish Constitutional Court dissolves pro-Kurdish party. Decision with serious consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court on Friday announced the dissolution of the country’s pro-Kurdish main party; a decision immediately followed by angry demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the southeast of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision threatens to make the work of the government enormously difficult, which is trying to reach out to the Kurdish community in order to put an end to the conflicts that have been going on for 25 years.
The "Party for a Democratic Society" (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a "site for activities that are detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," said Hasim Kiliç, president of the Constitutional Court, four days after the decision.
According to Kiliç, the decision was taken unanimously by 11 judges, with a majority of seven votes required to impose the dissolution, and he noted that 37 of the party’s leaders, including chairman Ahmet Türk and parliamentarian Aysel Tugluk, were excluded from political events for a period of five years.
Furthermore, the judge announced the lifting of parliamentary immunity, which Turkish and Tugluk enjoy, as well as the confiscation of the party's goods.
The DTP now has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
Before the verdict, the party leaders said that the parliamentarians would rather leave Parliament than meet like partyless parliamentarians.
The decision followed a trial initiated in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Turkish Federal Court, Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accused the DTP of following the “instructions” of the Kurdistan Workers’ Party (PKK), which Ankara and many other countries consider to be a terrorist organization.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
The party assures that it has “no connection” to the PKK, but refuses to call it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate.
The verdict of the Constitutional Court interferes with the government, which seeks to meet the Kurdish community and propose a series of measures to strengthen the rights of the Kurds in order to drain the support of the PKK by the Kurds and put an end to the conflicts.
The leaders of the DTP reaffirm that a dissolution could lead to a resurgence of tensions in southeastern Anatolia, where numerous demonstrations against the detention conditions of PKK chief Abdullah <0xC3><0x96>calan have led to clashes with police in recent weeks.
