The law enforcement forces used tear gas grenades and water cannons as the protesters began to throw Molotov cocktails and stones.
Hundreds of people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Türk assumed that the court's decision will "deepen the despair even further".
"Turkey cannot clarify this (Kurdish, annotated) question by means of a party's ban," he told the press.
The government, consisting of a party that emerged from the Islamist movement, also regretted the decision.
"We oppose, in principle, the closure of the parties.
That does not solve the problems," said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
"This decision is a torpedo to the democratic openness promoted by the government," said political market observer Ahmet Insel.
"One can obviously be prepared for a reaction from the PKK," he adds.
