Dream worlds
Some see images and hear voices that others don’t see or hear when they are awake.
Not only mentally ill people and the drug addiction blur the boundaries between imagination and reality.
As long as it happens in sleep, everything is fine.
When we lie in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we are free to surrender to the wildest ideas and imaginations.
However, those who experience traumatic states in waking up, see and hear things that others do not see or hear, are usually considered crazy or drug-addicted in the modern Western world, at least as a stranger.
But such images and voices are created not only in the case of mentally ill or in the drug rush.
The same neuronal processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels sometimes make the boundaries between dream, delusion and reality blur.
Traumatically altered wakefulness states can occur in a variety of forms, in the best case we call them visions, in the worst case madness.
Although triggers and effects may differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, shamanic rapture states, psychoses and hallucinations can be traced back to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions occur when the balance of the brain's neuronal messengers - especially dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine - derails and the interaction of different brain parts is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts very often occur during a schizophrenic psychosis.
Gravity no longer has power over him.
The connection between delusion and dream has engaged philosophers and physicians since antiquity.
Aristotle understood hallucinations as a form of dream in the waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, stated in 1861 a "great resemblance of misbehavior with dream states", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis, with all the inconsistencies, delusions, deceptions of such".
It is autumn 2001 when Henning T. turns into a comic character.
His body is two-dimensional and squeaky-colored.
Gravity no longer has power over him, he floats on the ceiling.
He feels a kick.
Behind him winged devil figures with blood-red, distorted frostbite, tooth-flashing.
They chase him, kick him with heavy, flaming boots, throw him against the walls, he feels the pain all over his body.
Loud, vicious voices roar from walls and radio.
He can no longer bear them, the voices that insult and insult him.
Henning T. pulls two cables from the stereo system, knots them to a loop and fastens them to a hook on the ceiling.
He climbs onto a loudspeaker and lays the loop around his neck.
Jump, jump.
The sling is loosened.
This is supposed to be a lesson for you, the voices scream in drum-feel ripping choir, "Go to the clinic and let yourself be healed!"
Today, Henning T. is 40 years old, he has experienced six acute psychoses, the last two years ago, the first almost 20 years.
It was triggered by LSD.
His diagnosis is schizoaffective-paranoid psychosis, besides, he is manic-depressive, he is taking medications for depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
In psychosis, I have experienced the worst fear and deepest despair, he says.
The illusions are cruel reality
About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in their lives, and in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, those affected are usually no longer able to differentiate between the internal and external worlds, they get into an overexcited state, which can lead to hallucinations, size, relationship or pursuit delusions.
Particularly common is hearing voices – voices that command, comment, or dialogue.
Even optical hallucinations are not uncommon.
The person affected can no longer separate important from unimportant, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like the dream, psychosis opens the gates to a flood of ideas and fantasies that originate in the deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, senior physician at the Department of General Psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of the action, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time, he gets into a passive role, he is, like in the dream, overwhelmed by the events and cannot actively shape them.
Schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
A comparison of reality is usually not possible for them, the deceptions are cruel reality, awakening excluded.
Having experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in the dream, Fuchs says, "but the sensual and spatial structure of reality, which is perceived in psychosis, remains fundamentally preserved."
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are rooted in reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in the real framework.
Why exactly our brain strikes caprioles, researchers still pose puzzles.
Exceptional conditions can cause any person to lose the relation to reality for a short time, says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that genes are not the sole determining factors.
Researchers assume that there is minimal brain damage in those affected.
We suspect that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disrupted at an early stage of development, by a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, for example, explains Fox.
But it remains a mystery how the disorder of the neural system comes about, which also initially does not manifest itself for many years at all.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be triggers for psychosis if the disposition is present.
Also, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychoses as they interfere with the transmitter system.
When Our Brain Is Running Hot
The crazy thing is, psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and swallow expensive drugs to get rid of them, while others spend money on drugs to get some, says Lübeckian psychology professor Erich Kasten.
Whether deceptive images are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often just a matter of point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and deceptive phenomena for ten years, last year he evaluated his results in the book "The irreal world in our head".
Hallucinations are among the typical concomitant symptoms of psychoses, but also of surprisingly many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, these often also include diseases such as migraines, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer’s and skull traumas.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, even the brain of healthy people hallucinates.
Hallucinations, according to Box, are composed of memory contents that are usually held back.
They arise when brain areas where sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or inhibited; when our brain is running hot or even when stimulation is lacking.
Drugs can trigger this condition just as much as brain damage or psychosis.
But also stimuli withdrawal, stress, love sorrow or other mental states of exception.
In recent studies, up to one-third of respondents reported having experienced hallucination at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attends the high school there.
A normal girl, actually.
If it weren't for the pictures and the voices.
During the break, it can happen that a sloppy boy with long, dark hair appeals to it.
When it answers him, the classmates look at it with surprise – no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think the shy girl is a shabby daydreamer, but Sarah K. doesn’t dream, she knows that.
She is awake, she hears and sees this boy, just as she hears and sees the girl in the bench next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for a moment.
A pleasant feeling is that she likes the boy.
Am I crazy? she asks sometimes.
But she knows that this boy and the other deceptives are not real and disappear again.
At night, the phenomena are usually frightening
Often, the deceptions are also a burden.
When she sits in the classroom, she can sometimes not follow the teaching material because the teacher is presenting a new classmate in her eyes and ears, while he explains mathematical equations to everyone else, both audible and visible on the table.
At night, the phenomena are usually frightening.
When she waits in her dark room for the sleep that comes far too rarely and far too late, she often cannot distinguish whether she is awake or already dreaming, whether the images she sees, the frills or the girl with the bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, arise in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, she screams at the figures.
Parents and friends don’t tell her about it, they would think she’s crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She passed high school last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Since she contacted the psychologist on the internet, she knows very well that she is not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art of despair
If someone is socially isolated or suffers from stimulus deprivation, they are highly likely to have hallucinations after a while, says Kasten.
I suspect the brain is then underemployed and provides its own entertainment.
Sarah K., a single child, was scared of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13 that the man she calls father since she can think is not her bodily father.
Because in visual and acoustic hallucinations, the same brain areas are active, which also process real impressions and sounds, it is difficult for those affected, such as Sarah K., to differentiate between deceptive images and reality.
Hallucinations are also images that create the brain, which is why they seem so real.”
Even nighttime dream images value caste as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their delusion as irreal.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to appreciate the hallucinations as a special ability.
The boundary between dream and hallucination
In our too conscious world, imaginary experience is unfortunately most often pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Department of Psychiatry and Psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
Psychosis is a serious, painful disease, but it also contains positive, creative - delusion is also a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has explored the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of traumatically altered awake consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams that the experiencer considers real and which he cannot distinguish from the waking state even in retrospect.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in trauma- or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis with full consciousness.
When a person is threatened by self-loss and world loss, for example by persistent, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own, imaginary world, which is decoupled from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of boundary state between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to cope with a situation in reality, a change in the world takes place, but the real situation is present in the imagination.
An intense form of meaning and meaning in an intrinsically unbearable situation that enables us human beings to create our own ability not to perish in a state of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Heart change" as a rescue action of the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness travels for days after a heart valve operation with subsequent heart transplantation, while his body is doomed to immobility in the intensive care unit.
Claussen dives into a self-made world, visits strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden, old man, aboard a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among nobles who make drugs from blood.
Abducted by a Greek on a motorcycle in his homeland, he surfs with his hospital bed in the snow of the Alps and meets a Korean mafioso.
It is completely absorbed in the imaginary event, everything is real, even later in memory.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dream is a different state, he describes his experience.
In contrast, the memories from mental travels are still clear to me after years and in minor details.
Clearer and more intense even than really experienced.
The intensity of this experience blows the horizon of our other life-world experiences, says the psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, oneiroids, psychoses, hallucinations and drug abuse show how fragile our inner images of external reality are even in waking.
Any change in the state of consciousness, the psychologist sums up caste, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be enriching.
