75% of working mothers have had problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the result of the study "Fertility and careers of women in Spain" carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Institute for Women.
The survey of 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working women see their career opportunities in the job market limited due to their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are major differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children, depending on whether the women work or not and, if so, what kind of profession they pursue.
Those of them who do not do any other work outside the home, work only half-day or do not have a permanent contract are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with permanent employment, especially in the public sector, postpone the establishment of a family and maternity and therefore have fewer children.
"The women in the age group between 35 and 49 with a permanent employment have their first child on average only 3.7 years after contracting, a figure that increases to 4.1 years for women with permanent employment who have taken longer to achieve this and who have realized their contracting and the first child much later.
Moreover, the type of work also has a major impact on maternity, albeit less than the calendar in terms of willingness to conceive,” explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account in the age of the women at the time of marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the age at the time of marriage and the first child is the higher the level of education.
This difference was also found in women of the same age.
For example, women in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, depending on whether they only graduated from primary school or graduated from higher education, became mothers for the first time on average with 25.1 or 32.1 each.
Furthermore, depending on their level of education, there is another difference between women.
While the women with a primary degree marry before their first permanent employment and have their first child, the women with a middle or high school degree do exactly the other way around and first seek a permanent employment and then marry and then have their first child, Delgado notes.
