Michelin and Fesvial together for the use of the helmet
In collaboration with the Spanish Foundation for Road Safety (Fesvial), the tyre manufacturer Michelin has launched a campaign to promote the use of helmets, especially among younger motorcyclists, as both companies announced today.
This initiative aims to draw attention to the importance of helmet use, as it is ultimately the only protective element that can prevent head injuries or even death in the event of a motorcycle accident.
Michelin pointed out that this campaign is part of its commitment to road safety, which "compasses far more than just designing and manufacturing products that become more and more safe every day", and further reaffirmed that it also contributes with other actions of an educational and informative nature to bring this goal one step closer every day.
This new campaign to promote the use of helmets on motorcycles, which runs under the slogan ‘To be or not to be’, will distribute posters to over 500 motorcycle workshops in a first phase to achieve the best possible distribution.
Finally, Michelin stressed that road safety is "a constant concern" of the company, and precisely for the reason that, as a manufacturer of tyres for two-wheeled vehicles, they are always committed to one of their main goals must be the development of ever safer products.
Sales of small trucks rise again
After almost two years, the car market for vans finally starts to see some light at the end of the dark tunnel.
The 9,425 vehicles registered in Spain in November represent an increase of 12.6% compared to 2008 and, more importantly, are the first ever increase after 22 consecutive months of steady decline, according to the figures presented by the manufacturers' association Anfac and the car dealers' association Ganvam.
However, these good figures are currently only to be enjoyed with great caution, since the reference data used for comparison are from November 2008, which was a particularly poor sales year with a decline of 60% with respect to the previous year.
