Assistance with braking manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As with the ABS anti-lock braking system and as with the ESP stability control, the auxiliary systems for braking in emergencies must become a mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly registered passenger cars and light vans, for the rest of the vehicles a waiting period has been set until the end of February 2011.
The measure adopted by the European Union aims to improve the protection of pedestrians, but due to their functioning, these braking systems can also help to prevent many collisions.
The task of the emergency braking assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical brake maneuver, which the system detects on the brake pedal based on the brake strength executed by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to a survey commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, one-third of the drivers involved in an accident before the collision did not even get to step on the brake pedal and half of them had not braked at full power.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force into the brake system and thereby reduces the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car travels during the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency braking assistant.
There would be even fewer accidents – one in four accidents could be prevented with personal injury – once the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that (via radar or a camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
When the driver reacts, the system helps him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if it becomes necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already inevitable, the brake assistant will apply maximum pressure to the brakes in order to keep the damage as low as possible.
