CNMV approves the public exclusion tender of Paternina submitted by the investment company Mer
The National Stock Exchange Commission (CNMV) approved the public exclusion tender for Federico Paternina submitted by the investment company Mer on 9 October.
The supervisory authority stated that it approved this invitation to tender after it had been demonstrated that the conditions complied with the enforceable laws and thus the content of the submitted explanatory supplement, following the amendments of 2 December, can be considered "sufficient".
CNMV has further announced that this offer is aimed at the acquisition of 550,008 shares of Federico Paternina at the price of 7.65 euros per share, which in turn represents 8.95 % of the share capital, which consists of 6,142,786 euros in shares admitted to the stock exchanges of Madrid and Bilbao.
It has also been announced that 5,592,778 million shares have been invested, which cannot in any way be transferred until the closing of the tender and the price of which has been fixed by Federico Paternina in accordance with the legally enforceable laws.
New Vehicle Assessment Programs
In these days of bad weather and accidents, not only the car workshops deserve
Every day, thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are dragged to the workshops, where an expert must assess the damage caused and the cost of the repair.
No single accident is the same and calculating the cost of the parts and working hours can be a long and complicated task.
The calculation of repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros by hand, including parts and working hours, can take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest computer tools, it is a matter of minutes
That is why almost 100% of assessors use this type of system.
Accident assessment and repair service providers collect the information they receive from manufacturers to process it afterwards and offer it to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American group Solera, is the market leader; 80% of all expertise is generated with their products.
The other two companies that compete in the tool market for reviewing and drafting a report are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data provided by the manufacturers is anything but easy.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, Sales Manager of Audatex, it works with 63 manufacturers and importers, each of whom provides the information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed is becoming ever greater, to the point that even more versions, variants and motorizations have come on the market in the last five years than in the entire fifteen years before.
As soon as a new car arrives on the market, the work begins for the companies.
It is a laborious task, because every single one of the thousands of vehicle parts must be cataloged and its price entered.
In addition, each model creates a "intelligent" graphic image on which you can "click" on different parts of the vehicle.
If this is a much-sold model, the work can be completed in a week if the procedure proceeds swiftly.
If it is a less common car, it can take up to three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of cars sold in Spain.
Among the more exclusive models, for example, they have information about the Porsche models, but not about Ferrari or Lamborghini.
In terms of the fleet of vehicles travelling on the roads, it is over 99%.
For the purpose of carrying out the documentation work and the production of databases, Audatex has eight centers distributed worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, the USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) and each of them specializes in specific brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>90 million annually in the development of these databases.
Every month, they record 2.5 million data and their customers receive the updates every other day.
The elaboration of this enormous flow of information allows companies to use it in different ways and thus offer different products.
The most common use is for repairs and repairs, but depending on the country, there are also tools for managing scrap parts or calculating the fault or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide who informs about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer this offer in Spain, but in the United States.
When reviewing the products Audatex offers, you can easily get an overview of the type of support it provides to industry experts.
This company offers ten different tools, the star of which is AudaPlus, a standard solution for assessing accidents for assessors.
It includes vehicles, motorcycles as well as light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it includes the repair times estimated by the manufacturer or the painting prices.
This tool is paid for depending on the purpose of use, i.e. for each expert report.
It will be most expensive for customers who rarely use it, a maximum of ten times a month, namely 5.75 euros per month.
On the other hand, every insurance company that produces thousands of opinions negotiates the price with Audatex.
With other products, such as AudaVIN, it is possible to fully identify a vehicle and the equipment with which it ran from the assembly belt, based solely on the chassis number.
AudaGlass deals with the vehicle windows, and AudaSubastas is an online service open to the specialist market that allows you to offer for vehicles that have been declared to be completely damaged.
